### Scenario 2: Serving `login.html` as a Static File

If you already have the HTML file, you can use Java to create a simple web server that just serves it. This example uses a server built into the JDK, requiring no external libraries.

**Steps:**
1.  Save the HTML above as a file named `login.html`.
2.  Save the Java code below as `SimpleFileServer.java` in the **same directory**.
3.  Compile and run `SimpleFileServer.java`.
4.  Open your web browser and go to `http://localhost:8080`.

**`SimpleFileServer.java`**
```java
import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpServer;
import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpHandler;
import com.sun.net.httpserver.HttpExchange;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.OutputStream;
import java.net.InetSocketAddress;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Paths;

public class SimpleFileServer {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        // Create a server on port 8080
        HttpServer server = HttpServer.create(new InetSocketAddress(8080), 0);

        // Create a context for the root URL "/" and set its handler
        server.createContext("/", new FileHandler());

        // Use the default executor
        server.setExecutor(null); 

        // Start the server
        server.start();
        System.out.println("Server started on port 8080. Access at http://localhost:8080");
    }

    static class FileHandler implements HttpHandler {
        @Override
        public void handle(HttpExchange exchange) throws IOException {
            try {
                // Read the login.html file into a byte array
                byte[] fileBytes = Files.readAllBytes(Paths.get("login.html"));

                // Set response headers: 200 OK and the content length
                exchange.sendResponseHeaders(200, fileBytes.length);

                // Get the response body stream and write the file content
                OutputStream os = exchange.getResponseBody();
                os.write(fileBytes);
                os.close();

            } catch (IOException e) {
                String response = "Error: File not found.";
                exchange.sendResponseHeaders(404, response.length());
                OutputStream os = exchange.getResponseBody();
                os.write(response.getBytes());
                os.close();
            }
        }
    }
}
```

