### Scenario 3: Parsing HTML with Jsoup

This is for when you want to read an HTML document and extract data from it. The **Jsoup** library is the standard for this in Java.

**You will need:**
*   The Jsoup library added to your project.

**Maven Dependency:**
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.jsoup</groupId>
    <artifactId>jsoup</artifactId>
    <version>1.17.2</version>
</dependency>
```

**`HtmlParser.java`**
```java
import org.jsoup.Jsoup;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Document;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Element;
import org.jsoup.select.Elements;

public class HtmlParser {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // The HTML content we want to parse
        String htmlContent = "<!DOCTYPE html>"
            + "<html lang=\"en\">"
            + "<head>"
            + "    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">"
            + "    <title>Login Page</title>"
            + "</head>"
            + "<body>"
            + "    <h2>Login Form</h2>"
            + "    <form action=\"/login\" method=\"post\">"
            + "        <label for=\"username\">Username:</label><br>"
            + "        <input type=\"text\" id=\"username\" name=\"username\" required><br><br>"
            + "        <label for=\"password\">Password:</label><br>"
            + "        <input type=\"password\" id=\"password\" name=\"password\" required><br><br>"
            + "        <input type=\"submit\" value=\"Login\">"
            + "    </form>"
            + "</body>"
            + "</html>";

        // Parse the HTML string into a Jsoup Document object
        Document doc = Jsoup.parse(htmlContent);

        // --- EXAMPLES OF EXTRACTING DATA ---

        // 1. Get the page title
        String title = doc.title();
        System.out.println("Page Title: " + title);

        // 2. Get the main heading (h2)
        Element heading = doc.select("h2").first();
        System.out.println("Heading: " + heading.text());

        // 3. Find the form and get its 'action' attribute
        Element form = doc.select("form").first();
        String formAction = form.attr("action");
        System.out.println("Form Action URL: " + formAction);

        // 4. Find the username input field by its ID
        Element usernameInput = doc.select("#username").first();
        String usernameNameAttr = usernameInput.attr("name");
        System.out.println("Username input 'name' attribute: " + usernameNameAttr);

        // 5. Find all labels and print their text
        Elements labels = doc.select("label");
        System.out.println("\nFound Labels:");
        for (Element label : labels) {
            System.out.println("- " + label.text());
        }
    }
}
```

